out and talking to women more.  I know thats not hugh, but I take it as a good thing b/c they are encounters that most likely would not have happened.  I think a lot of people use the game as a subconcious excuse to not do stuff in real life.  Now the piece they showed first was a little to the extreme, but from the number of people I have got to know on the game, it happens a lot.<br>
<br>
As far as the piece on the guy who killed himself, they protrayed that whole thing for something it wasnt.  From what I got from the piece, he fell in love with someone in EQ and probably found out it was a man in RL or that she was married and went into depression.  Now, if you have a child that is pretty well adjusted and is living in a kept up apartment and all of a sudden he stops cleaning up and letting you in, wouldnt you do something about it?  Especially since the kid had a mental handicap that he already had to deal with.  <br>
<br>
Overall I think the segment was good in the aspect of showing how addictive the game can be, but I think it lost me by trying to portray the game as being evil.  The interview she did with the creator was the best if you ask me b/c he said exactly how it was. <p><p align="center"><b><font size="2">Revnick Lifeweaver</font></b><font size="2"> 
