784frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=233.topic&index=13>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Interesting piece on 48 hrs tonight</span><hr size=1> According to my handy dandy dictionary it defines addiction as:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Compulsive physiological and psychological need for a habit-forming substance.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If someone drinks 3 beers a night, would you consider him/her an alcoholic? Take Homer Simpson for example, he goes to the bar with friends and drinks close to every night. Would you consider him a alcoholic? Most people would. Exchange alcohol with Everquest. Most players log in every night and play for 2 hours or more.  To some people EQ is something they need and must have. It can be many things from depression, lack of friends, etc that makes you need to log into EQ night after night. Because in EQ you are popular, you have a lot of friends, people depend on you, and so on.<br>
<br>
Bad day at work? Nothing a little EQ can solve. Your wife left you?…. and so on<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Quote from Caeadarie:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
I find it comical that of everything happening in the world, 48 hours felt it necessary to point of the evils of a computer game! <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I personally felt it was necessary to point out. EQ is ruining peoples lives right and left, and they don't even realize it because they are so far gone into EQ. How many people in EQ do you know that have gotten a divorce because of the game? How many people in EQ do you know that has lost their job because of EQ, etc?  And after that happens their addiction just gets worse. <br>
NOTE: Caeadarie, I’m not flaming you, I just decided to use your reply as a quote, nothing personal. =-)<br>
<br>
I have two RL friends that play EQ, my first fiend has tried to quit over and over, lately he quit for 3 months and I thought he was done with EQ. He started playing again a week ago.... My other friend couldn't go more than 2 weeks without logging in.<br>
<br>
I quit EQ about 7 months ago, and if I got the Internet where I lived I can guarantee I would be playing EQ right now. The only way I could kick my habit was to move somewhere else, disconnect my phone and my Internet. And for the first couple of months it was hard... very hard. At one point I ordered Internet service and went out to buy a modem. At the store I just stood there and looked at the modem I was about to buy going over everything... It took all of my strength to force myself to walk out of that store and not go back.<br>
<br>
Seven months later I only have a very slight desire to log in. But I won't lie, there is still a very small desire to log back in and see all of my old friends, but I know I can't. But on the other hand I have put my addictive habits on other things, such as video games. But the difference is I may beat Kingdom Hearts in 4 days with a total of 45 hours, but it ended and my life went back to normal... With EQ the game never ended.<br>
<br>
<br>
I know most of you think you don't have a problem, and say to yourself I can quit anytime... try it then, it's not as easy as you think. <br>
<br>
Everquest is a drug, it fills in that hole of your life. Everyone has something they hate about themselves, and for most of us EQ fills in that hole. The same can be said about heroin, alcohol, etc. I know right now your saying that EQ shouldn't be compared to a drug, it's not damaging to you.  Well how much weight have you gained since you started playing? How many nights have you only gotten 4 hours of sleep because you played too long? Most of the problems with EQ are not physical but psychological. <br>
<br>
I saw the 48-hrs show and I liked what John Smeadly said about EQ being a game. That you need the will power to say enough is enough and step back before it becomes more than a game. It is very easy to get addicted to EQ, and before you know it you can't quit and it's a part of your life. I didn't have that will power and EQ controlled my life for a long time, I would stay up late at night, show up late to work the next day, run home after work and play EQ all night. I was very moody and showed pretty much every sign of being an addict.<br>
<br>
But this isn't always the case for everyone. It is very possible to have a very normal life and play EQ. The difference is that person doesn't depend on EQ and doesn't &quot;need&quot; to play EQ. If you depend on EQ, and can't live without it then you are so very addicted. <br>
<br>
Sorry for the long reply. ^_^<br>
<br>
- Brian <p><hr><center><table border=0 cellspacing=6 cellpadding=6><tr><td><center><font size=6 face="Times New Roman">Ryoji Kaji</font><br><font size=3 face="Times New Roman">~ Retired ~</font></center></td><td><img src=http://www.webpost.net/br/brianrands/kitten.jpg></td></tr></table></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/bguild75784.showUserPublicProfile?gid=revnicklifeweaver>Revnick Lifeweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Scowls at you rdy to attack!</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#333333>(10/24/02 5:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub59.ezboard.com/fguild75784frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=233.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Interesting piece on 48 hrs tonight</span><hr size=1> Well said man <p>&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;Revnick Lifeweaver&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt; <br>
